Featuring new works (from over 70 internationally renowned contemporary artists) inspired by the beloved fantasy film, as well as never-before-seen original film production art (including hundreds of meticulously restored frames) and a pop-up shop offering an array of exclusive merch, @thelastunicorn40 group show will reunite fans, old and new. 💕💕💕

📆Opening December 17th, 7-11pm 🎉
📧 To request a preview of the exhibition:
jch@coreyhelfordgallery.com
🔗thelastunicorn40th.com

In his memoir, Topcraft animation studios director Katsuhisa Yamada writes: “The Last Unicorn was the result of the pure and constant efforts of all the staff: We may have crated some kind of magical effect.” In his milestone celebration, made possible by two very determined fans, for fans, Sweet Streets is proud to present for the first time a window into the making of this animated classic, alongside a whole new generation of artists inspired by its artistry.

All under the same roof, attendees will get a chance to experience a "behind-the-scenes" look at the film, shop the exclusive 40th anniversary capsule collection, and enjoy new works from a generation of artists inspired by the film’s unique artistry. The show is part of a two-year global celebration in honor of the film’s 40th anniversary.

Every mural has its hurdles, and this one was no exception. The wall I flew out to paint turned out to be over twice the size I was told. Unfortunately, I only had a small window in between projects, and I'm going to have to hit pause for now. I'm more than a bit embarrassed leaving this painting unfinished, but everyone involved has been great, and I will be back very soon to finish her up! Thank you so much to the community who have been so incredibly kind and supportive. I can't always hear you, but I appreciate you. ❤️🎧❤️
While I wait on security to let me start the next project, here's some more in progress shots of the last

No one: Got any mural tips?

Me: When I'm working on large-scale portraits, I tend to get lost in the details, and the drawing can easily shift while I build up forms. When I'm up on the lift, face to face with the painting, everything looks alright, but when I'm on the ground, I can tell things are a bit off. A good trick is to lay your reference over your painting and mark off where you've gotten lost.

social_posts.post_text: It was an honor to work with Kevin Barry Art Advisory and Emanate Health Queen of the Valley Hospital to bring a couple walls on their new cancer center to life. The murals are meant to represent the hospital and community while also commemorating the 100 year anniversary of West Covina, where it resides. Ellen Beach Yaw, Benjamin Franklin Maxson, Jr., and Sister Columba (Josephine Kohler) are the three historical figures represented on the left.
